research/history/round_summaries/round_0162.json:80:    "self_review": "\u8fd9\u8f6e\u9075\u5b88\u67b6\u6784\u63a2\u9488\u89c4\u5219\uff0c\u53ea\u6539\u4e00\u4e2a\u4e3b\u53d8\u91cf architecture\uff0c\u5e76\u4fdd\u6301\u4e3b\u7ebf\u7684 K\u3001EF\u3001optimizer\u3001LR \u4e0d\u53d8\u3002\u9009\u62e9 topk \u662f\u56e0\u4e3a\u5b83\u662f\u5f53\u524d\u5c1a\u672a\u5728\u8fd9\u4e00\u4e25\u683c matched \u914d\u65b9\u4e0b\u8865\u9f50\u7684\u6700\u7b80\u5355\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u57fa\u7ebf\uff0c\u80fd\u7528\u4e00\u6b21\u6700\u4f4e\u590d\u6742\u5ea6\u5bf9\u7167\u56de\u7b54\u201c\u4e3b\u7ebf\u7ed3\u6784\u662f\u5426\u771f\u7684\u5fc5\u8981\u201d\u8fd9\u4e2a\u5269\u4f59\u95ee\u9898\u3002",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:7:  "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 15 established `topk/signum/LR=1.6e-3/EF=12` at `K=64` as a valid new Pareto point, so the next most informative single-variable question is whether LUTurbo can push cost lower again without collapsing reconstruction. This round changes only `K`, moving from `64` to `32` while keeping the same family and recipe fixed, to measure the next step on the cost-quality frontier.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:20:    "summary": "Continue the topk low-K tradeoff lane: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and reduce `K` from `64` to `32` to test whether a materially cheaper decomposition still yields an acceptable reconstruction curve.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:23:    "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active topk family, changes exactly one primary variable, and follows directly from the new `K=64` keep result. The main risk is a sharp FVU jump at `K=32`, but mapping that boundary is now more valuable than more K128 recipe polishing because LUTurbo's objective is total online cost, not only anchor quality.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:30:        "value": "topk"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:51:      "Round 15 added a credible `K=64` Pareto point on the accepted topk/signum/LR1.6e-3/EF12 backbone.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:57:      "If `K=32` degrades sharply, `K=64` may be the practical low-K sweet spot for the current topk recipe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:69:    "architecture": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:78:    "description": "Continue the topk low-K tradeoff lane: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed, and reduce `K` from `64` to `32` to test whether a materially cheaper decomposition still yields an acceptable reconstruction curve.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0016.json:79:    "self_review": "This stays on the active topk family, changes exactly one primary variable, and follows directly from the new `K=64` keep result. The main risk is a sharp FVU jump at `K=32`, but mapping that boundary is now more valuable than more K128 recipe polishing because LUTurbo's objective is total online cost, not only anchor quality.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0181.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_factorized_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0181.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `lowrank_factorized_residual` under the unchanged mainline recipe (`K=128, EF=2, signum, lr=3.0e-3`). Final reconstruction is `x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i`, where `U(Vx)` is a static low-rank trunk and the residual coefficients are chosen by a factorized scorer but still decode as a finite weighted sum over a static residual dictionary `B`. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`: LUTurbo/Lottable can export the trunk factors and residual dictionary as static vector libraries, then run `trunk branch + factorized support scoring + weighted sparse lookup-sum` online. The single question is whether a lower-cost factorized residual selector is worth continuing versus the current two-stage soft-codebook mainline in the low-EF feasible regime. This probe should stay safely within the encoder-cost budget and gives a clean read on whether scorer factorization is a viable architecture direction rather than another likely policy reject.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0181.json:20:    "summary": "Probe `lowrank_factorized_residual` as the one matched architecture change. It is LUTurbo-exportable (`\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`) through a static low-rank trunk plus static residual dictionary, and it tests whether factorized residual scoring is worth continuing against the current soft-codebook two-stage mainline in the low-EF feasible regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0181.json:23:    "family_name": "lowrank_factorized_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0181.json:30:        "value": "lowrank_factorized_residual"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0181.json:51:      "`lowrank_factorized_residual` is LUTurbo `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`: the factorized encoder changes selector-side scoring only; decode remains a finite weighted sum over static trunk and residual libraries.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0181.json:57:      "If `lowrank_factorized_residual` underperforms on FVU and/or slows throughput without a compensating cost advantage, mark factorized residual scoring as not worth continuing in the current low-cost regime."
