research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 23 showed that increasing `AUXK_ALPHA` above the `topk/signum/K128/EF12/LR=1.6e-3` reference did not improve the anchor recipe, which suggests the mainline is likely saturated on auxiliary-loss magnitude itself. This round changes only `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD`, lowering it from the effectively inactive `10000000` to `100000`, to test whether earlier dead-feature rescue improves late-stage reconstruction or curve shape without changing the core topk recipe.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:20:    "summary": "Run a single loss-schedule test on the exact topk mainline reference recipe: keep `ARCHITECTURE=topk`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125` fixed, and reduce `DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD` to `100000` to see whether activating auxiliary rescue earlier helps the K128 baseline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:23:    "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `topk` family, changes only one non-core variable on the exact reference backbone, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the evidence that both weaker and stronger `AUXK_ALPHA` failed to beat the baseline. The main risk is that the threshold change may have little effect over this training horizon, but it is the cleanest remaining single-variable way to probe whether the auxiliary mechanism is mis-timed rather than mis-scaled.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:30:        "value": "topk"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0024.json:61:      "Judge this run by full curve shape as well as final FVU: if earlier rescue smooths late descent or lowers FVU, the issue was activation timing; if not, the current topk/signum/K128 recipe is likely saturated on the aux-loss path."
